Interview Questions
1) What is a non-static variable in Java?
-->In Java, a non-static variable (often called an instance variable) is a variable that is declared within a class but 
    outside of any method, constructor, or block, without using the static keyword.



2) Where are non-static variables stored in memory?
-->They are stored in the heap memory, inside the object.
    Instance Variables (Heap Memory): 
    Local Variables (Stack Memory):


3) When are non-static variables created and destroyed?
-->Created → when an object is created using new
    Destroyed → when the object is garbage collected (no references exist)


4) Can non-static variables be accessed without creating an object? Why or why not?
-->❌ No
    Because they belong to objects, not the class.    
    👉 You must create an object to access them.


5) Can we use ‘this’ keyword with static variables? Why or why not?
-->❌ No
    this refers to the current object
    Static variables belong to the class, not any object
    👉 So this cannot be used with static context



6) What is the default value of a non-static variable if not initialized?
-->
| Data Type        | Default Value |
| ---------------- | ------------- |
| int              | 0             |
| float/double     | 0.0           |
| boolean          | false         |
| object reference | null          |
| char             | '\u0000'      |




7) If we modify a non-static variable using one object, will that affect another object?
-->❌ No
    Each object has its own copy of non-static variables.
    class Test {
        int x = 10;
    }
    👉 Changing x in one object does not affect another.



8) What is java.lang.NullPointerException, and how can we handle it?
-->A NullPointerException occurs when you try to use a null reference like an object.

    String str = null;
    str.length(); // Exception
    Handling:
    Check for null before use
    Use try-catch
    if (str != null) {
        str.length();
    }



9) Can we print an object directly? Explain toString() method.
-->Yes, you can print an object directly in Java by passing it to methods like System.out.println(). When you do this, 
  the Java compiler internally invokes the object's toString() method to obtain a string representation for display. 
    System.out.println(obj);
    
    👉 Internally calls:
    
    obj.toString();
    
    The toString() method is an instance method defined in the Object class, which is the root of the inheritance hierarchy in Java.
    Because every class inherits from Object, every object has a toString() method. 
    
    Default Behavior: If you do not override toString() in your class, the default implementation from the Object class is used. 
    It returns a string consisting of the class name, the @ symbol, and the hexadecimal representation of the object's hash code 
    (e.g., MyClass@1a2b3c4d).
    
    Purpose: Its main goal is to provide a textual representation of an object. This is primarily used for debugging, logging, 
    and displaying human-readable information about an object's state.




10) Difference between memory locations of static and non-static variables.
-->
| Feature         | Static Variables | Non-Static Variables     |
| --------------- | ---------------- | ------------------------ |
| Belongs to      | Class            | Object                   |
| Memory Location | Method Area      | Heap                     |
| Copies          | One copy         | Separate copy per object |
| Access          | Class name       | Object reference         |




