1) Can a static method directly access a non-static variable? Explain with an example.
-->❌ No, because:
    
    Static methods belong to the class
    Non-static variables belong to an object
    ✅ Example:
    class Demo {
        int x = 10;
    
        static void show() {
            // System.out.println(x); ❌ Compile-time error
    
            Demo obj = new Demo(); // create object
            System.out.println(obj.x); // ✅ access through object
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            show();
        }
    }
    
    👉 Static method needs an object reference to access non-static data.




2) Create a class with one static and one non-static variable. Print their values after creating multiple objects
to show the difference in behavior.
-->class Test {
          static int a = 0;  // static
          int b = 0;         // non-static
      
          void increment() {
              a++;
              b++;
          }
      }
      
      public class Main {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              Test obj1 = new Test();
              Test obj2 = new Test();
      
              obj1.increment();
              obj2.increment();
      
              System.out.println("obj1 -> a: " + obj1.a + ", b: " + obj1.b);
              System.out.println("obj2 -> a: " + obj2.a + ", b: " + obj2.b);
          }
      }
      🔹 Output:
      obj1 -> a: 2, b: 1
      obj2 -> a: 2, b: 1
      
      👉 Explanation:
      
      a → shared (static) → incremented twice
      b → separate (non-static) → each object has its own copy



